import{a as e}from"./chunk-BDBX6WDC.js";import"./chunk-IFGU66OU.js";var t={meta:e,sections:[{id:"overview",title:"Overview",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"A **distributed cache** is an in-memory key-value store, spread across many nodes, that sits in front of slower data stores to serve reads in **sub-millisecond** time. It is the workhorse behind nearly every system in this catalog (Netflix's EVCache, Twitter's timelines, Instagram's feeds). This design builds one from scratch: a Redis/Memcached-style cluster with **consistent hashing**, **replication**, **eviction**, and defenses against the classic failure modes."},{type:"callout",variant:"info",title:"The big idea",body:"Three problems define a distributed cache: (1) **placement** \u2014 which node owns a key, and how to add/remove nodes without remapping everything (consistent hashing); (2) **memory management** \u2014 what to evict when full (LRU/LFU) and when entries expire (TTL); and (3) **resilience** \u2014 replication, failure detection, and surviving hot keys + cache stampedes."},{type:"image",src:"assets/diagrams/distributed-cache-architecture.svg",alt:"Distributed cache: client sends GET/SET to a smart client that hashes the key and routes to the owning node on a consistent-hashing ring, with virtual nodes and replication to the next nodes clockwise.",caption:"A smart client hashes each key to a position on the ring and routes to the owning node; keys are replicated to the next nodes clockwise."}]},{id:"clarifying-questions",title:"Clarifying Questions",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:'"Design a distributed cache" can mean a generic Redis clone or a purpose-built cache for one workload. Spend the first **3-5 minutes** pinning down the use case and non-functional priorities before drawing the ring diagram.'},{type:"table",caption:'Questions to ask, and reasonable assumptions if the interviewer says "you decide".',headers:["Question","Why it matters / sample assumption"],rows:[["Is this a general-purpose cache, or built for a specific workload (e.g. session store, leaderboard)?","General-purpose GET/SET/DELETE with TTL \u2014 like designing a Redis/Memcached-style cluster from scratch."],["What scale \u2014 working set size, ops/sec, average entry size?","Assume ~1TB working set, ~1M ops/sec cluster-wide, ~1KB average entry \u2014 this drives the node count and replication factor math."],["Does data need to survive a restart (persistence), or is it acceptable to lose it and repopulate from source?","It is a cache, not a database \u2014 losing data on restart is acceptable; the source of truth lives elsewhere."],["What consistency is required between the cache and the backing database?","Eventually consistent, bounded by TTL, using cache-aside with invalidate-on-write \u2014 not strict consistency."],["Is a specific eviction policy expected (LRU/LFU), or is choosing and justifying one part of the exercise?","Default to LRU and justify it; mention LFU/W-TinyLFU as a follow-up for scan-resistant workloads."],["Single region or must the cache serve multiple regions with low latency everywhere?","Start single-region; mention cross-region replication or per-region clusters as a scaling extension."],["How important is defending against hot keys / cache stampedes for this workload?","Assume it matters (a viral key or expiring popular key is a realistic interview follow-up) \u2014 design request coalescing and TTL jitter in from the start."],["Should clients talk directly to cache nodes (smart client), or through a proxy?","Assume a smart client (avoids an extra hop); mention proxy-based routing (twemproxy) as the simpler alternative for thin clients."]]},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"Say your assumptions out loud",body:'For example: "I will treat this cache as AP \u2014 available and fast, tolerating staleness \u2014 since the source of truth lives in the database and cache data is always recoverable." Stating the CAP trade-off up front anchors every later decision (async replication, eviction, invalidation) and shows the interviewer you are choosing deliberately, not by default.'}]},{id:"functional-requirements",title:"Functional Requirements",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"We scope this to a general-purpose cache cluster."},{type:"bestPractices",title:"In scope",practices:["**GET / SET / DELETE** by key, with optional **TTL**.","**Eviction** when memory is full (LRU / LFU).","**Horizontal scaling**: add/remove nodes with minimal key movement.","**Replication** for availability + read scaling.","**Failure detection** and automatic recovery.","**Hot-key + stampede** mitigation."]},{type:"callout",variant:"note",title:"Out of scope (state this explicitly)",body:"Rich data types (Redis lists/sets/streams), Lua scripting, persistence/AOF as a primary store, transactions, and pub/sub. We focus on the core distributed key-value cache. Mentioning these shows you know a real Redis does much more."}]},{id:"non-functional-requirements",title:"Non-Functional Requirements",blocks:[{type:"prosCons",title:"Prioritizing the qualities",pros:["Ultra-low latency: sub-millisecond GET/SET (it must be faster than the DB it fronts).","High throughput: hundreds of thousands to millions of ops/sec per node.","High availability: a node loss must not take down the cache.","Horizontal scalability with minimal rehashing.","Predictable memory usage with graceful eviction."],cons:["Durability is NOT required \u2014 a cache can lose data (it is repopulated from source).","Strong consistency with the backing store is NOT guaranteed (it is a cache).","Occasional stale reads are acceptable (bounded by TTL)."]},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"CAP framing",body:"A cache leans **AP**: stay available and fast, tolerate staleness. Because the source of truth lives elsewhere, losing cache data is recoverable \u2014 so we optimize for **latency and availability** over consistency and durability. That single trade-off shapes every other decision here."}]},{id:"capacity-estimation",title:"Capacity Estimation",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Suppose we need to cache **1 TB** of hot data, average value **~1 KB**, serving **1M ops/sec** at the cluster level, with each node holding **~64 GB** of usable cache memory."},{type:"metrics",items:[{label:"Working set",value:"~1 TB",hint:"hot data to cache"},{label:"Avg entry size",value:"~1 KB",hint:"key + value + overhead"},{label:"Entries",value:"~1B",hint:"1 TB / 1 KB"},{label:"Throughput",value:"~1M ops/s",hint:"cluster-wide"},{label:"RAM / node",value:"~64 GB",hint:"usable for cache"},{label:"Nodes (RF=3)",value:"~48",hint:"1TB/64GB \xD7 3 replicas"}]},{type:"markdown",value:"Node count is driven by memory and replication, not CPU. With replication factor 3:"},{type:"math",display:!0,tex:"N_{nodes} = \\left\\lceil \\frac{DataSet \\times RF}{RAM_{node}} \\right\\rceil = \\left\\lceil \\frac{1\\,\\text{TB} \\times 3}{64\\,\\text{GB}} \\right\\rceil \\approx 48\\ \\text{nodes}",caption:"Node count = (working set \xD7 replication factor) / per-node RAM, plus headroom for overhead and growth."},{type:"markdown",value:"Per-node throughput also matters: 1M ops/sec across ~48 nodes is ~21k ops/sec each \u2014 comfortably within a single node's capability (a tuned in-memory store does 100k+/sec), leaving headroom for hot-shard skew."}]},{id:"single-node",title:"Single-Node Cache Internals",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Before distributing, get one node right. The core is a **hash map** for O(1) lookup plus an **eviction policy** to bound memory. The classic design for **LRU** is a hash map combined with a **doubly-linked list**: the map gives O(1) access, the list tracks recency so the least-recently-used entry is evicted in O(1)."},{type:"code",language:"java",filename:"LruCache.java",highlightLines:[8,9,10,16,17],code:`// O(1) get/put LRU: HashMap for lookup + doubly-linked list for recency.
class LruCache<K, V> {
  private final int capacity;
  private final Map<K, Node<K, V>> map = new HashMap<>();
  private final DoublyLinkedList<K, V> recency = new DoublyLinkedList<>();

  V get(K key) {
    Node<K, V> n = map.get(key);
    if (n == null) return null;
    recency.moveToFront(n);          // mark most-recently-used
    return n.value;
  }

  void put(K key, V value, long ttl) {
    Node<K, V> n = map.computeIfAbsent(key, k -> recency.addFront(k, value));
    n.value = value; n.expireAt = now() + ttl;
    recency.moveToFront(n);
    if (map.size() > capacity) {
      Node<K, V> lru = recency.removeLast();   // evict least-recently-used
      map.remove(lru.key);
    }
  }
}`},{type:"callout",variant:"info",title:"Expiration: lazy + active",body:"TTLs are enforced two ways. **Lazy**: on access, if an entry is expired, treat it as a miss and remove it. **Active**: a background job samples random keys and evicts expired ones (Redis does exactly this) so dead entries do not hog memory forever even if never read again."},{type:"callout",variant:"note",title:"Concurrency + memory layout",body:"Real caches shard the keyspace into segments each with its own lock (or run single-threaded like Redis to avoid locks entirely), and use slab allocation (Memcached) to avoid memory fragmentation from variable-size values."}]},{id:"eviction-policies",title:"Eviction Policies",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"When memory is full, something must go. The policy hugely affects hit ratio. The common choices trade simplicity against how well they predict future access."},{type:"featureComparison",caption:"Common eviction policies.",columns:["LRU","LFU","FIFO","Random"],rows:[{feature:"Evicts least recently used",values:[!0,!1,!1,!1]},{feature:"Evicts least frequently used",values:[!1,!0,!1,!1]},{feature:"Handles scan/one-hit-wonders",values:[!1,!0,!1,!1]},{feature:"O(1) implementation",values:[!0,!1,!0,!0]},{feature:"Good general default",values:[!0,!1,!1,!1]}]},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"LRU is the default; LFU resists pollution",body:"**LRU** is the sensible default. But a big sequential scan can **pollute** an LRU cache, evicting genuinely hot keys for one-time reads. **LFU** (or a hybrid like Redis's approximated LFU, or W-TinyLFU) tracks frequency so a one-hit-wonder never displaces a popular key. Mention the scan-pollution failure to show depth."}]},{id:"consistent-hashing",title:"Consistent Hashing",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"The defining distributed-systems problem: which node owns a key, and what happens when nodes change? A naive `hash(key) % N` remaps **almost every key** when N changes \u2014 catastrophic for a cache (a mass miss storm). **Consistent hashing** places both keys and nodes on a ring; a key belongs to the first node clockwise, so adding/removing a node only moves the keys in **one segment**."},{type:"math",display:!0,tex:"\\text{keys moved on node change} \\approx \\frac{K}{N} \\quad\\text{vs}\\quad \\text{(naive modulo)} \\approx K\\left(1 - \\tfrac{1}{N}\\right)",caption:"Consistent hashing moves only ~1/N of keys when a node is added/removed; modulo hashing moves nearly all of them."},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"Virtual nodes fix imbalance",body:"With few physical nodes, the ring is lumpy \u2014 some nodes own much larger arcs than others. **Virtual nodes** (each physical node placed at many points on the ring) smooth the distribution and make rebalancing on failure spread across the whole cluster, not onto a single unlucky neighbor."},{type:"code",language:"python",filename:"consistent_hash.py",highlightLines:[6,7,14,15],code:`import bisect, hashlib

class HashRing:
    def __init__(self, nodes, vnodes=150):
        self.ring = {}            # hash -> physical node
        self._keys = []           # sorted hashes
        for n in nodes:
            for v in range(vnodes):           # virtual nodes for balance
                h = self._hash(f"{n}#{v}")
                self.ring[h] = n
                bisect.insort(self._keys, h)

    def node_for(self, key):
        h = self._hash(key)
        i = bisect.bisect(self._keys, h) % len(self._keys)  # first clockwise
        return self.ring[self._keys[i]]

    def _hash(self, s):
        return int(hashlib.md5(s.encode()).hexdigest(), 16)`}]},{id:"high-level-architecture",title:"High-Level Architecture",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Clients use a **smart client** (or a proxy) that knows the ring topology, hashes the key, and routes the request directly to the owning node \u2014 avoiding an extra hop. Nodes exchange membership/health via **gossip**. Each key is replicated to the next few nodes clockwise for availability."},{type:"mermaid",caption:"Smart-client routing + gossip-based membership + replication.",definition:`flowchart TD
  App["Application"] --> SC["Smart Client (knows ring)"]
  SC -->|hash(key) \u2192 owner| N1["Node 1 (primary for key)"]
  N1 -->|replicate| N2["Node 2 (replica)"]
  N1 -->|replicate| N3["Node 3 (replica)"]
  N1 <-->|gossip: health, topology| N2
  N2 <-->|gossip| N3
  N3 <-->|gossip| N1
  Config[("Topology / config")] -.-> SC`},{type:"featureComparison",caption:"Client-side routing vs proxy vs server redirect.",columns:["Smart client","Proxy (e.g. twemproxy)","Server redirect (Redis Cluster)"],rows:[{feature:"Extra network hop",values:[!1,!0,!1]},{feature:"Thin/simple clients",values:[!1,!0,!0]},{feature:"Central scaling bottleneck",values:[!1,!0,!1]},{feature:"Client must know topology",values:[!0,!1,!0]}]},{type:"architectureCard",title:"Smart Client",description:"Library embedded in the app that caches the ring topology, hashes keys, routes to the owner, retries replicas on failure, and refreshes topology on membership changes. Removes a proxy hop for lowest latency.",icon:"shuffle",tags:["routing","topology","low-latency"]},{type:"architectureCard",title:"Cache Node",description:"In-memory store (hash map + eviction + TTL) owning a set of ring segments. Serves GET/SET, replicates writes to followers, participates in gossip, and re-shards its keys when topology changes.",icon:"server",tags:["in-memory","eviction","replication"]}]},{id:"replication",title:"Replication",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Replication serves two goals: **availability** (a replica takes over when the primary dies) and **read scaling** (reads can fan out to replicas). Each key's primary replicates to the next **RF-1** nodes clockwise on the ring. The trade-off is **sync vs async** replication."},{type:"prosCons",title:"Synchronous vs asynchronous replication",pros:["Async: lowest write latency (ack immediately, replicate in background).","Async: primary throughput unaffected by slow replicas.","Sync: no data loss on primary failure (replica already has the write)."],cons:["Async: a brief window where a crash loses the most recent writes.","Sync: higher write latency (wait for replica acks).","Sync: a slow replica drags down every write."]},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"For a cache, async usually wins",body:"Since a cache tolerates data loss (repopulate from source), **asynchronous replication** is the common choice \u2014 it keeps writes fast and the cluster available. Use synchronous/quorum replication only when the cache stores data that is expensive or impossible to recompute."}]},{id:"consistency",title:"Consistency",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"There are two consistency questions: **within the cache** (primary vs replicas) and **between the cache and the database**. Both are typically **eventually consistent**, bounded by TTL. The harder, more famous problem is **cache\u2013DB coherence**: keeping the cache from serving stale data after the DB changes."},{type:"featureComparison",caption:"Cache write/invalidation patterns.",columns:["Cache-aside","Write-through","Write-behind"],rows:[{feature:"App manages cache",values:[!0,!1,!1]},{feature:"Cache writes to DB",values:[!1,!0,!0]},{feature:"Write latency",values:["Low","Higher","Low"]},{feature:"Risk of stale on miss",values:[!0,!1,!1]},{feature:"Risk of data loss",values:[!1,!1,!0]}]},{type:"callout",variant:"warning",title:"Invalidate, don't update, on writes",body:'After a DB write, **deleting** the cache entry (so the next read re-populates from the DB) is generally safer than updating it in place \u2014 concurrent updates can interleave and write a stale value last. "Delete on write, lazily repopulate on read" avoids most cache\u2013DB races. Beware the subtle read-then-write race; a short TTL bounds any residual staleness.'}]},{id:"cache-stampede",title:"Cache Stampede & Hot Keys",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Two notorious failure modes. A **cache stampede** (thundering herd): a popular key expires and thousands of concurrent requests all miss and hammer the DB simultaneously to recompute it. A **hot key**: one key is so popular its owning node is overwhelmed. Both can cascade into an outage."},{type:"bestPractices",title:"Stampede mitigation",practices:["**Request coalescing / locking**: the first miss recomputes; others wait for the result (single-flight).","**Early/probabilistic expiration**: refresh a key slightly *before* it expires so it never goes fully cold.","**Stale-while-revalidate**: serve the old value while one worker refreshes in the background.","**TTL jitter**: randomize TTLs so many keys do not expire at the same instant.","**Pre-warm** known-hot keys after a deploy/restart."]},{type:"code",language:"python",filename:"single_flight.py",highlightLines:[4,5,6],code:`def get_or_compute(key, recompute, ttl):
    val = cache.get(key)
    if val is not None:
        return val
    # Single-flight: only one caller computes; others block on the lock.
    with cache.lock(f"lock:{key}", blocking=True, timeout=5):
        val = cache.get(key)          # double-check after acquiring lock
        if val is None:
            val = recompute()          # the one DB hit
            cache.set(key, val, ttl_with_jitter(ttl))
        return val`},{type:"callout",variant:"warning",title:"Hot key mitigation",body:"For a single overwhelmingly-hot key, sharding the ring does not help (it is one key on one node). Mitigate by **replicating the hot key to multiple nodes** and load-balancing reads, adding a **client-side local cache** for ultra-hot keys, or appending a small random suffix (`key:0..N`) to spread it \u2014 then aggregating."}]},{id:"membership-failure",title:"Membership & Failure Detection",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Nodes join, leave, and crash. The cluster needs **decentralized membership** and **failure detection** without a single point of failure. A **gossip protocol** spreads health/topology: each node periodically exchanges state with a few random peers, so knowledge of a failure propagates across the cluster in logarithmic time."},{type:"mermaid",caption:"Gossip propagates a node failure.",definition:`flowchart LR
  N1["N1 (detects N3 down)"] -->|gossip| N2["N2"]
  N1 -->|gossip| N4["N4"]
  N2 -->|gossip| N5["N5"]
  N4 -->|gossip| N6["N6"]
  N5 -->|"N3 down"| All["...whole cluster converges"]`},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"Phi-accrual + heartbeats",body:'Rather than a binary "up/down" from a single missed ping, use **heartbeats** with a **phi-accrual failure detector** that outputs a suspicion level adapting to network conditions. This avoids flapping (prematurely declaring a slow-but-alive node dead and triggering needless rebalancing).'},{type:"callout",variant:"note",title:"Rebalancing on membership change",body:"When a node is added or confirmed dead, only the keys in the affected ring segments move (thanks to consistent hashing). Replicas are promoted, new replicas are created on the next nodes, and the smart clients refresh their topology view via gossip/config."}]},{id:"api-design",title:"API Design",blocks:[{type:"apiTable",title:"Core cache operations",endpoints:[{method:"GET",path:"GET key",description:"Fetch a value (null on miss/expired)",auth:!1},{method:"PUT",path:"SET key value [TTL]",description:"Store a value with optional expiry",auth:!1},{method:"DELETE",path:"DEL key",description:"Invalidate a key",auth:!1},{method:"POST",path:"INCR key",description:"Atomic counter increment",auth:!1},{method:"POST",path:"CAS key old new",description:"Compare-and-swap (optimistic)",auth:!1},{method:"GET",path:"MGET k1 k2 ...",description:"Batch fetch (one round-trip)",auth:!1}]},{type:"markdown",value:"Most cache traffic is **GET**, so the protocol is a compact binary request/response (like the Memcached/RESP protocol) over a long-lived TCP connection with pipelining. **MGET** batches lookups to amortize round-trips; **CAS** and **INCR** provide just enough atomicity for counters and optimistic updates."},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"Pipelining + connection pooling",body:"Network round-trips dominate at sub-ms latencies. Smart clients **pipeline** multiple commands on one connection and maintain **connection pools** per node to keep latency low and avoid per-request handshakes."}]},{id:"scaling-strategy",title:"Scaling Strategy",blocks:[{type:"bestPractices",practices:["**Scale out** by adding nodes to the ring; consistent hashing moves only ~1/N of keys.","**Virtual nodes** keep load balanced as the cluster grows/shrinks.","**Replicas absorb read load** for hot ring segments.","**Client-side near-cache** for ultra-hot keys to cut network traffic entirely.","**Partition by use-case**: separate clusters for different workloads to isolate blast radius.","**Monitor hit ratio + p99 latency + evictions** \u2014 the cache's vital signs."]},{type:"callout",variant:"info",title:"Hit ratio is everything",body:"A cache's value is its **hit ratio**. A drop from 99% to 95% means the backing store sees a **5\xD7** increase in load (misses go from 1% to 5%). Sizing, eviction policy, and TTLs should all be tuned to protect the hit ratio \u2014 and you should alarm on it."}]},{id:"availability",title:"Availability",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"A node loss must degrade, not break, the system. Replicas take over failed primaries; smart clients retry the next replica on a timeout. Critically, a cache failure should **never** take down the application \u2014 on a cache miss or node outage, the app falls back to the source of truth."},{type:"callout",variant:"warning",title:"Beware the miss-storm on cold start",body:"If a whole cache tier restarts cold, every request misses and stampedes the DB \u2014 which can collapse the whole system. Mitigate with **gradual warm-up**, **request coalescing**, **load shedding** at the DB, and replica failover that preserves a warm copy rather than starting empty."},{type:"callout",variant:"summary",title:"Graceful degradation",body:"Treat the cache as an optimization, not a dependency: misses and outages fall back to the source. Protect the backing store from miss-storms with coalescing and jittered TTLs so a cache problem never cascades."},{type:"youtube",videoId:"iuqZvajTOyA",title:"Designing a distributed cache (illustrative embed)"}]},{id:"partitioning",title:"Partitioning",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"The keyspace is partitioned across nodes by the consistent-hash ring; virtual nodes ensure each physical node owns roughly equal load. This is partitioning at the infrastructure level \u2014 the cache *is* the partitioning mechanism that other systems rely on."},{type:"callout",variant:"warning",title:"Avoid hot partitions",body:"A skewed key distribution (one viral key, or a poor key design that funnels traffic to one segment) creates a hot node. Virtual nodes help with *range* skew but not a *single* hot key \u2014 for that, use hot-key replication or client near-caching (see the hot-key section)."}]},{id:"fault-tolerance",title:"Fault Tolerance",blocks:[{type:"bestPractices",practices:["**Replication (RF\u22652)** so a single node loss never loses a ring segment's availability.","**Client retry to replicas** on timeout, with short deadlines (fail fast to the DB).","**Gossip + phi-accrual** detection to avoid flapping and needless rebalancing.","**Request coalescing** so failures/expiries do not stampede the source.","**Bulkhead clusters** per workload to contain blast radius.","**App-level fallback** to the source of truth on any cache failure."]},{type:"expandable",title:"Example: read with replica failover",blocks:[{type:"code",language:"python",filename:"get_with_failover.py",code:`def get(key, ring):
    nodes = ring.preference_list(key, n=3)   # primary + replicas, clockwise
    for node in nodes:
        try:
            return node.get(key, timeout_ms=20)   # fail fast
        except (Timeout, NodeDown):
            continue                              # try the next replica
    return None   # total miss \u2192 caller falls back to the source of truth`}]}]},{id:"trade-offs",title:"Trade-offs",blocks:[{type:"table",caption:"Key decisions and what they cost.",headers:["Decision","Gain","Cost"],rows:[["Consistent hashing + vnodes","Minimal rehash, balanced load","More complex than modulo"],["Async replication","Fast writes, high availability","Small data-loss window"],["Smart client routing","No proxy hop, low latency","Fat clients, topology in client"],["LRU eviction","Simple, good default","Scan pollution (vs LFU)"],["Invalidate on write","Avoids cache-DB races","Extra miss to repopulate"],["AP / no durability","Speed + availability","Staleness; cold-start miss-storms"]]}]},{id:"technology-choices",title:"Technology Choices",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"How real systems implement each piece:"},{type:"table",headers:["Concern","Real-world example"],rows:[["In-memory store","Redis / Memcached"],["Sharding","Redis Cluster (hash slots) / consistent hashing"],["Client routing","Smart clients (Lettuce/Jedis) / twemproxy"],["Membership","Gossip (Redis Cluster bus, SWIM)"],["Eviction","LRU / LFU / W-TinyLFU (Caffeine)"],["Replication","Primary\u2013replica, async"],["Multi-AZ cache","Netflix EVCache (on Memcached)"],["Failure detection","Phi-accrual / heartbeats"]]},{type:"callout",variant:"note",title:"Redis Cluster uses hash slots",body:"Rather than a pure hash ring, **Redis Cluster** maps keys to **16384 fixed hash slots**, and slots to nodes. Resharding moves slots (not individual keys), which is operationally simpler. It is a pragmatic variant of the same consistent-hashing idea \u2014 worth mentioning as the production reality."},{type:"code",language:"yaml",filename:"cache-cluster.deploy.yaml",code:`service: cache-node
replicationFactor: 3
vnodesPerNode: 150
eviction: lru
maxmemory: 64gb
maxmemoryPolicy: allkeys-lru
failureDetector: phi-accrual
autoscaling:
  metric: memory_used_pct
  target: 75
  min: 6
  max: 200`}]},{id:"interview-questions",title:"Interview Questions",blocks:[{type:"interviewQa",items:[{question:"Why consistent hashing instead of hash(key) % N?",answer:"With modulo, changing N remaps almost every key, causing a mass cache-miss storm that hammers the DB. **Consistent hashing** places keys and nodes on a ring so adding/removing a node only moves ~1/N of keys (the affected segment). **Virtual nodes** keep load balanced across uneven cluster sizes."},{question:"How do you implement an O(1) LRU cache?",answer:"Combine a **hash map** (O(1) key lookup) with a **doubly-linked list** ordered by recency. On access, move the node to the front; on insert past capacity, evict the tail (least-recently-used). Both operations are O(1)."},{question:"What is a cache stampede and how do you prevent it?",answer:"When a hot key expires, many concurrent requests miss and all recompute it against the DB at once (thundering herd). Prevent it with **request coalescing/single-flight** (one caller computes, others wait), **early/probabilistic refresh**, **stale-while-revalidate**, and **TTL jitter** so keys do not expire simultaneously."},{question:"How do you handle a single hot key?",answer:"Sharding does not help \u2014 it is one key on one node. **Replicate the hot key to multiple nodes** and balance reads, add a **client-side local cache** for it, or split it with a random suffix (`key:0..N`) and aggregate. Detect hot keys via per-key metrics."},{question:"How do you keep the cache consistent with the database?",answer:"Use **cache-aside** with **invalidate-on-write**: after a DB update, delete the cache entry so the next read repopulates from the DB. Deleting beats updating in place (avoids interleaved-write staleness). A short **TTL** bounds any residual staleness; for stronger needs, write-through."},{question:"How do nodes detect failures without a central coordinator?",answer:"A **gossip protocol**: each node periodically exchanges health/topology with random peers, so failure knowledge spreads in logarithmic time. Pair it with **heartbeats + a phi-accrual detector** to output an adaptive suspicion level and avoid flapping on transient slowness."},{question:"When would you choose LFU over LRU (or vice versa)?",answer:"**LRU** is the right default for most access patterns and is O(1) to implement with a hash map + doubly-linked list. **LFU** (or an approximation like W-TinyLFU) wins when the workload includes large one-time scans that would otherwise evict genuinely popular keys under LRU \u2014 it tracks actual access frequency so a one-hit-wonder cannot displace a hot key. The cost is more bookkeeping (frequency counters, decay) and a less intuitive eviction order to reason about operationally."},{question:"How would you extend a single-region cache cluster to serve multiple regions?",answer:"Run an independent cache cluster per region (own ring, own nodes) so regional latency stays low and a region outage stays contained \u2014 this mirrors how the backing databases are usually partitioned geographically too. For data that must be shared across regions, replicate asynchronously between clusters or accept that each region warms its own cache independently from the source of truth. Avoid a single global ring: cross-region hops would defeat the whole point of sub-millisecond latency."},{question:"How do you decide how much memory to allocate per node and how many nodes you need?",answer:"Start from the working set size and replication factor: `nodes = ceil(workingSet \xD7 RF / ramPerNode)`, then check the per-node throughput implied by dividing total ops/sec across that many nodes against a single node's realistic capacity (100k+ ops/sec for a tuned in-memory store). Leave headroom (20-30%) for uneven key distribution and growth, and re-derive the numbers whenever the working set or replication factor changes \u2014 this is the same capacity-estimation exercise as sizing any other tier, just bound by RAM instead of disk."}]}]},{id:"references",title:"References",blocks:[{type:"references",items:[{label:"Consistent Hashing and Random Trees (original paper)",url:"https://www.cs.princeton.edu/courses/archive/fall09/cos518/papers/chash.pdf",source:"Karger et al."},{label:"Redis Cluster Specification",url:"https://redis.io/docs/latest/operate/oss_and_stack/reference/cluster-spec/",source:"Redis"},{label:"Memcached",url:"https://memcached.org/",source:"Memcached"},{label:"Netflix EVCache",url:"https://netflixtechblog.com/caching-for-a-global-netflix-7bcc457012f1",source:"Netflix"},{label:"SWIM: Scalable Membership Protocol",url:"https://www.cs.cornell.edu/projects/Quicksilver/public_pdfs/SWIM.pdf",source:"Cornell"}]}]},{id:"summary",title:"Summary",blocks:[{type:"callout",variant:"summary",title:"Key takeaways",body:`1. **Get one node right** (hash map + doubly-linked list for O(1) LRU, plus lazy + active TTL expiry), then distribute.
2. **Consistent hashing with virtual nodes** places keys on nodes so adding/removing a node moves only ~1/N of keys and keeps load balanced.
3. **Replicate (async) for availability + read scaling**, and detect failures with **gossip + phi-accrual** to avoid flapping.
4. **Defend against stampedes and hot keys**: single-flight, TTL jitter, stale-while-revalidate, hot-key replication, client near-caches.
5. **It is a cache, not a database**: AP over CP, invalidate-on-write for DB coherence, and always fall back to the source so a cache failure never cascades.`}]}]},i=t;export{i as default};
